1. Git Fundamentals (Must be crystal clear)

    If this is weak, everything breaks later.

    Core concepts
    What is Git (distributed VCS vs centralized)
    Working Directory vs Staging Area vs Repository
    Commits and snapshots (not file differences)
    Commands you MUST master
    git init
    git clone
    git add
    git commit
    git status
    git log
    git diff

    👉 Understand:

        What happens internally when you run git add and commit
        How Git tracks changes (hashes, blobs, trees)
2. Branching & Merging (Very Important for real work)
Concepts
    Branch = pointer to commit
    HEAD
    Fast-forward vs 3-way merge
Commands
    git branch
    git checkout / git switch
    git merge
Must understand
    Merge conflicts (how they happen + resolution)
    Feature branching workflow
3. Remote Repositories (Team collaboration)
Concepts
    Origin
    Upstream/downstream
    Fetch vs Pull
Commands
    git remote
    git fetch
    git pull
    git push

👉 Learn difference:

    git pull = fetch + merge
    When to use fetch vs pull
4. Rebasing (Advanced but VERY important)
Commands
    git rebase
    git rebase -i (interactive)
Must understand
    Rebase vs Merge (very common interview question)
    Clean commit history
    Squashing commits

⚠️ Rule:
    Never rebase public/shared branches
5. Git Internals (This makes you expert level)
    Concepts
    SHA-1 hashes
    Objects:
        Blob
        Tree
        Commit
    .git folder structure

👉 Learn:
    How commits are stored
    How branches are just pointers
6. Undoing & Fixing Mistakes (Real-world critical)
Commands you MUST know deeply
    git reset (soft, mixed, hard)
    git revert
    git checkout -- <file>
    git restore

👉 Difference:
    Reset = rewrite history
    Revert = safe undo (new commit)
7. Stashing & Temporary Work
    git stash
    git stash pop
    git stash list

Use case:
    Switching branches without committing
8. Cleaning & Maintenance
    git clean
    git gc
    .gitignore
9. Tags & Releases
    git tag
    Annotated vs lightweight tags

Used in:
    Production releases (v1.0, v2.0)

10. Advanced Workflows (Industry Level)
Learn these workflows:
    Git Flow
    GitHub Flow
    Trunk-based development

👉 Understand:
    Feature branches
    Release branches
    Hotfix branches
11. Git in DevOps (Very important for YOU)

Since you're into DevOps, focus here 👇

CI/CD Integration
    Git with Jenkins pipelines
    Webhooks
    Auto build on push
Tools you should know
    GitHub
    GitLab
    Bitbucket
Concepts
    Pull Requests (PR)
    Code reviews
    Branch protection rules
12. Advanced Expert-Level Topics
Must learn if you want mastery:
    Cherry-pick (git cherry-pick)
    Bisect (git bisect) → debugging tool
    Submodules
    Monorepo strategies
    Large file handling (Git LFS)
    Hooks (pre-commit, pre-push)
13. Debugging & Troubleshooting
    Fix merge conflicts like a pro
    Recover deleted commits (git reflog)
    Fix broken repo
